title: For Sale:  Armscor Rock Island M200 Revolver, .38 Special, Like New, In Box, Papers, Hogue Grip,  $220, CCW Discount
location: Wildwood, Chesterfield, Eureka, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
This is a solid, budget friendly revolver modeled after the Colt Anaconda & King Cobra designs, manufactured by Armscor. Armscor is headquartered in the Philippines and has been making firearms since 1952. They offer a lifetime warranty, so if you ever have an issue with this revolver, you are covered.

Here are some detailed reviews of this gun http://ezine.m1911.org/showthread.php?140-Armscor-M200-Series-Revolver-Review and https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UfAeAn7PS3Y

About Armscor https://us.armscor.com/heritage/history
Product Page https://us.armscor.com/products/m200-38-special
Armscor Warranty info https://us.armscor.com/support-center/

This gun makes an ideal “spare” or “stash away” gun thanks to its price and  parkerized finish (traditionally used on military weapons), which is extremely tough, resistant to the mother nature, and requires no TLC.

Note this is NOT officially  rated for the higher pressure +P rounds, though enthusiasts who claim to have contacted Armscor say they were told it is acceptable to use +P on occasion, but frequent use will accelerate wear & tear. Since Armscor  is providing a lifetime warranty, one can conclude that is why +P  is not officially endorsed. I used no +P in this gun. In non +P ammo, for home protection and personal defense use, I recommend Hornady’s “Critical Defense” round.  That said, if the purpose of this gun is to spend its life in a quick access safe in a nightstand drawer, guarding against a home intruder,  load it with +P.

I got this new in March 2015, fired exactly 36 rounds and it shoots to point of aim, tested at 7 yards, single action (hammer pre-cocked), my target below, all in the 10 ring with 4 in the X ring.  Gets the job done well.  Note the tight side-to-side variance (the most important one)  is only about an inch as shown by the Silver Dollar,  and centered around the X …  that’s the performance you hope for in a fixed sight gun that you never know for sure about until you shoot it.  Note this was done without any kind of gun/hand rest, so it’s capable of even tighter shot grouping, especially in the up & down variance.  The single action trigger pull is quite crisp and nice. Double action is appropriately firm, but still smooth.  I’m only selling because I was attracted to its concept and value, but have since acquired other revolvers and I want to help pay for those.  It’s worth what I’m asking, as it’s cheaper than new, good as new, and offers proven point-of-aim = point-of-impact, which is something you never can know for sure on a fixed sight gun until you shoot it. Everything pictured is included … box, instruction manual, test fired case, literature. Exactly what you’d get if purchased new, plus you’re saving sales tax and/or shipping and FFL fees if you ordered from an online retailer. Freshly cleaned and oiled, ready to go.

BONUS … I added the Hogue one-piece overmolded pebble finish grip to this, which cost $25. This grip is outstanding and really makes for a comfortable, cushioned feel that fits like a glove, as well as absorbs recoil.  I’m throwing in no charge, and will provide the original two-piece grip panels as well, but you’ll never want to put those back on after feeling the Hogue. I also painted the front sight bright orange and then clear nail polish and it stands out well in sun and low light. Easily removed if desired, but recommend keeping it versus the stock black-on-black sight picture.

Note … Must be a MO resident, provide Driver’s License or equivalent ID as proof and complete a bill of sale.  By purchasing this firearm you are confirming you are able to legally purchase and possess a firearm.  You are not purchasing this firearm for someone that is not legally able to do so (a.k.a "straw man" purchase).

$20 discount for showing your  CCW license, that would make this an outstanding value for any CCW’er … an enhanced gun thanks to the Hogue grip, good as new, proven to shoot to point-of-aim, with a lifetime warranty.

Specs: 6 round capacity, .38 Special, fixed sights, 6” sight radius,  dark grey/black oxide finish, 28 ounce weight.

title: For Sale/Trade:  CZ P09 Duty .40S&W kit with light
postcontent:
I bought this pistol for myself, then my brother bought me one as a gift, so now I have two of them. This thing is essentially brand spanking new in the box with everything that comes with it from the factory. 2 mags, all the different sized back straps, a lock, a safety (came with a decocker installed that you can swap for a manual safety, pretty sweet feature) and (shockingly) a damn nice rail-mounted light that even has a strobe feature. Yeah, they just threw that in from the factory, pretty cool I know. 

Anyway, this is the second generation P-09 where they re-did a couple things. Primarily I guess they messed with the feed ramp and the magazine followers a bit because the first generation had some feed issues. My limited experience with this pistol has been flawless, and the ergonomics are really top of the range for the budget-tier polymer framed pistols...also the stipling is super nice and they put it in all the rice places. This thing is seriously good to go as a nightstand or glove box pistol. I've had more than a few CZs down the years, and they're as reliable as any Glock or Sig or you-name-it that I've ever owned, just really high quality and high value pistols. If I weren't obsessed with purging redundancy from my collection, I'd just keep the thing. 

The pic below is from Google because I'm not at home to take an actual picture of the kit, but it looks exactly like what you see in that pic. It's immaculate, I only got it like a month ago.
